And that's just the ERC721! Thanks to all the big ğŸ§ s helping us tackle these gas prices. ğŸ™

By allowing the developer to provide their own implementation Solmate doesn't need to include the String library or unnecessary functions. This is very appreciated by those of us that like on-chain data URIs.
4c https://t.co/Nmn7mhZvXl

They also assume that the token id will be included in the URI. This requires the function to change the token from an unsigned integer into a string.
4b https://t.co/DSbt6Kx9IY

4) Opinions About Token URI
@OpenZeppelin makes assumptions about the structure of a token's URI.

First, an internal function to returns a base URI. This can be overridden in the child contract.
4a https://t.co/KoYNgns9Iz

Solmate makes the mapping public to satisfy the same interface. This means an extra view function isn't necessary.
3b https://t.co/c2NHDni4wr

3) Unnecessary Private Mappings

IERC721 defines a public balanceOf function. @OpenZeppelin satisfies this implementation by keeping a private mapping of balances and a read function to access that mapping.
3a https://t.co/mROhTdazZJ

Solmate ERC721 reduces deployment cost.

How?

By removing:

1) Transfer hooks (get fucked enumerable)
2) Address
3) Unnecessary private mappings
4) Opinions about the token URI

Deeper dive into 3 and 4 ğŸ‘‡ https://t.co/kd41yebR2o
